{
  "answer": "**The maqta (final couplet, incorporating the poet's takhallus 'Zauq') of the ghazal in *Diwan-E-Zauq*, chapter 16 (\"Ek sadma dard-e-dil se meri jaan par toh hai\"), reads as follows in translation:**\n\n> O Zauq, a heart that has no fire of love  \n> Is worse than stone, which has a fiery core, at least.[^1]\n\n**In transliteration (from the radif-bearing maqta line):**\n\n> Woh dil ke jiss mein soz-e-mohabbat na hove 'Zauq'  \n> Behtar hai sang uss se ke uss mein sharar toh hai[^2]\n\nThis concludes the 10-couplet ghazal, as confirmed by the chapter's closing stanza and wiki card.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, ch. 16 (\"Ek sadma dard-e-dil se meri jaan par toh hai\"), [paragraph](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/16-ek-sadma-dard-e-dil-se-meri-jaan-par-toh-hai/translation/#p-df8cda).\n\n[^2]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, ch. 16 (\"Ek sadma dard-e-dil se meri jaan par toh hai\"), [paragraph](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/16-ek-sadma-dard-e-dil-se-meri-jaan-par-toh-hai/transliteration/#p-df8cda).\n\n[^3]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, ch. 16, [chapter](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/16-ek-sadma-dard-e-dil-se-meri-jaan-par-toh-hai/translation/).",
